            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Robert Miller was born and raised in San Francisco, a city whose hills and fog were as familiar to him as his own reflection. His parents, blue-collar workers themselves, instilled in him the values of hard work and practicality. Growing up in a modest Sunset District home, Robert attended local public schools, finding early satisfaction in fixing things around the house. Academically, he gravitated towards hands-on tasks rather than theoretical studies, finding his stride in shop classes and practical skills.\n\nUpon finishing high school, Robert wasn't drawn to the typical college path. Instead, he found work doing maintenance for a small independent school, learning on the job and developing a keen understanding of building systems. This laid the foundation for his career. He eventually transitioned to a facilities maintenance role within a larger educational institution, a stable position that offered decent benefits and a predictable routine. Over the years, he's become a seasoned professional, the silent operator keeping the lights on and the heat running.\n\nA significant turning point came in his early 30s when a long-term relationship ended. This period of introspection led him to appreciate the stability his career provided and to find solace in his routine and the tangible results of his work. He learned to enjoy his own company, dedicating time to tinkering with various projects and exploring the lesser-known corners of the city.\n\nRobert's social circle is small but meaningful. He maintains a close relationship with his aging mother, still residing in the Sunset. He has a few long-time friends from his youth, individuals who understand his quiet nature and shared history in the city. His colleagues are a work family, a source of camaraderie and shared experiences in the often-unseen world of building maintenance.\n\nLooking ahead, Robert's aspirations are modest and centered on security and peace of mind. He dreams of owning a small property outside the city someday, a place where he can pursue his passion for hands-on projects without the constraints of urban living. He hopes to ensure his mother is comfortable and well-cared for.\n\nHis current lifestyle is defined by routine. His days begin early, commuting via public transportation, a familiar journey through city streets. His work is physical and engaging, a constant puzzle of problem-solving. Evenings are quiet, often spent reading, watching old movies, or working on a small repair project. He enjoys exploring San Francisco's parks and hidden staircases on weekends, a low-key way to connect with the city he calls home. Robert's connection to San Francisco isn't about the trendy new spots, but about the enduring fabric of the city, the neighborhoods that have watched him grow, and the quiet satisfaction of knowing his work helps keep them functioning."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. The memory of helping his dad fix the rattling dryer drum in the basement, the metallic clinking echoing through the small space.  The immense satisfaction of the quiet hum after it worked, his dad's approving nod, instilled in him a deep sense of accomplishment from hands-on work, a feeling that would guide him for years. It was during his childhood.\n\n2. After the breakup, walking the desolate beach at Ocean Beach one foggy evening, the vastness of the Pacific mirroring his own emptiness. The cold wind on his face brought a surprising clarity, a quiet resolve to find strength within himself and appreciate the stability his steady job offered. This was in his early 30s.\n\n3. The moment his aging mother, frail but smiling, held his hand and thanked him for always looking out for her. Her gratitude, simple and heartfelt, solidified his commitment to her well-being above all else, reminding him of the quiet fulfillment found in caring for those you love. This is ongoing, becoming more significant in recent years.\n\n4. Finding a forgotten, intricate clock mechanism in a dusty corner of the school\u2019s maintenance room. Spending hours meticulously cleaning and reassembling it, the intricate gears clicking back into place, was a profound lesson in patience and the beauty of hidden functionality, mirroring his own role in the building. This occurred early in his facilities career.\n\n5. Sitting on a bench in Dolores Park, watching the diverse flow of city life beneath him, feeling a quiet sense of belonging not to a trend, but to the bedrock rhythm of San Francisco. This simple, repeated act solidified his deep, understated connection to the city, a connection built on familiarity and hidden corners rather than bright lights. This is a recurring memory throughout his life."
